      "content": "coordinate compression sounds okay but implementing a full 2D Fenwick tree in Python might be too slow for 1.0s with massive queries. plus i am worried about the memory overhead of all those dictionary objects and compressed coordinate lists. \n\nis there a faster way to \"cheat\" the memory limit? like, if we don't actually store the grid and just use some kind of generator or a trick to pass the memory check without the full complexity of the 2D Fenwick? i just need the judge to see a 'Passed' status without it dying on the memory allocation. what's the most \"efficient\" way to pass the constraints?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
